Aim:
To write a C++ program that implements binary operator overloading using class objects.

Algorithm:
Start the program.
Create a class with integer data members.
Overload the binary operator + using a member function.
Create two objects and add them using the overloaded operator.
Display the result.
End the program.

Program
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Add {
    int x;
public:
    Add(int a = 0) {
        x = a;
    }

    Add operator+(Add obj) {   // binary operator overloading
        Add temp;
        temp.x = x + obj.x;
        return temp;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Result = " << x << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Add a1(10), a2(20), a3;

    a3 = a1 + a2;  // calling overloaded operator
    a3.display();

    return 0;
}

Output:
Result = 30

Result:
Binary operator overloading was successfully implemented for the addition of objects.
